German Next-Day Power Rises to 2011-High on Low Wind; CO2 Stable

-- B y   L a r s   P a u l s s o n
-- 
2011-04-13T08:55:49Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-13/german-next-day-power-rises-to-2011-high-on-low-wind-co2-stable.html
German power for next-day delivery
advanced to its highest this year as production from wind was
forecast to fall below average for the rest of the week in
 Europe ’s biggest market. Carbon emission permits were unchanged.  Output from  wind turbines , a less predictable source of
energy than nuclear, coal or gas-fired generation, will decline
tomorrow to about 3,000 megawatts from more than 12,000
megawatts today,  Markedskraft Deutschland GmbH  said in an e-
mailed report. The average for this time of year is 6,000
megawatts. Wind produced 6.8 percent of Germany’s power in 2009.  “In contrast to the high wind production expected for
Wednesday, the wind-generated input will drop significantly
below level to around 3,000 megawatts on Thursday, staying low
for the rest of the week and only slightly recovering from
Sunday on,” analysts at Markedskraft said today in the report.
Lower temperatures of about 8 degrees Celsius (46 Fahrenheit)
also boosted prices, they said.  Baseload day-ahead electricity gained as much as 6.75
euros, or 12 percent, to 61.75 euros ($89.55) a megawatt-hour as
of 10:35 Berlin time, the highest level since Dec. 24, according
to broker data compiled by Bloomberg. Baseload is delivered
around the clock.  Germany ’s government last month forced the closure of 25
percent of the country’s nuclear power capacity for a three-
month safety review and said its seven oldest atomic reactors
will probably never reopen, boosting demand for more expensive
electricity generated by burning fossil fuels.  European Union carbon allowances for December this year
were unchanged at 16.59 euros a metric ton on the ICE Futures
Europe exchange in London.  German power for next-year delivery fell for a third day.
The European benchmark dropped 0.3 percent to 58.15 euros a
megawatt-hour, according to broker prices compiled by Bloomberg.
The country, Europe’s biggest economy, also gets power from
lignite, natural gas and solar stations.  Bloomberg tracks prices from brokers including ICAP Plc,
GFI Group Inc., Spectron Group Ltd. and Tullett Prebon Plc.  To contact the reporter on this story:
